                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>toopik wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">For getting to the bottom of the aggro list - it's never aggro management that I have a problem with, it's always initial aggro off a mez resist.  Dopple seems to work fine for me once in a while, and I'd put more points into the ability if it reduced the timer &gt;&lt;  I want a tool that <span style="font-weight: bold">helps</span> us mez.  Not an "oh shit" button #5.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I have to take exception to this opinion.  My perspective is quite a bit different, even though we are seeing the same problem.
<br />

<br />
When you have a multipull you have usually a single mob with some direct aggro on the puller, and you have one or more mobs with proximity aggro, and they are all incoming <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
You stand there like the cocky bitch chanter we all are, you target the add and cast mez, and it resists, and now you are not only at the top of the aggro list, but you are really the only one to have done anything to make it mad beyond the lame proximity aggro the puller has.  You are screwed with few options here.
<br />

<br />
Well, you can try kiting.  This works on some mobs, even some OOW mobs, but there are others (and several of them) that will catch you and spank you like a morning, eh, you know, and no speedy feet buff is going to make you outrun them as they race circles around bards.
<br />

<br />
You can have an aggro buddy in the group.  I do this most of the time now out of necessity.  Preference is a ranger/druid who can snare and also keep me in SOE.  When I get a resisted mez, they try to ensnare or root the mob, either way they pull aggro and kite a while as I try again to mez (which sometimes bounces again and the cycle repeats).
<br />

<br />
Or, you can look to the development team and repeatedly point out that, "Hey, you retards seriously overlooked something when you made these mobs hit so hard and still expect us to take a beating with our low AC and relatively low HP!"
<br />

<br />
An ability to drop you to the bottom of the aggro list when a mez bounces does fulfill a very vital function.  You would automatically lose aggro, period.  Unlike 'boggle' or 'soothing waste of aa points' this would be a drop in aggro to a fixed amount that would be near zero, but would not be fading memories.  It would give you a way to recover and try to mez again.  
<br />

<br />
But, everything in game is all about the aggro list and maintaining your position on it.  If you are at the top, you need to be the tank.  If you get to the top, you need a way to get lower on the list or you get squishied.  Many classes have abilities that will automatically make them not be the top of the aggro list.  We have no such ability or spell.  We have the ability to reduce aggro, and we have the ability to sometimes totally clear all aggro, but we have no way to drop ourselves on the aggro list with any level of reliability.
<br />

<br />
So, there we are.  We have a mob that just resisted mez, we have tons of aggro, nobody else is doing anything to make the mob mad, and it is coming after us.  What is the Sony vision for the sequence of events that follows?  My guess is they just simply don't know.
<br />

<br />
Stasis is your get out of resisted mez for free every 72 minutes ability.  If you get a resist, and you can live for 2 more seconds (time for it to cast), then you will be fine, this time.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Danyela on Fri Nov 12, 2004 10:06 pm; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
